{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"telegram:8212808444\",\n  \"message_id\": \"24074\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8212808444\",\n  \"sender\": \"B G\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-05-01 14:17 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"B G (8212808444)\",\n  \"id\": \"8212808444\",\n  \"name\": \"B G\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"cf141110","parentId":"fc90a09d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T18:17:11.479Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"95c022db","parentId":"cf141110","timestamp":"2026-05-01T18:17:27.382Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby wants to build \"Telephone\" - a voice chat interface. Let me think through what I need to build:\n\n1. **Frontend (local HTML page)** — Dark themed, fairy lights animation that reacts to:\n   - When user speaks (user's audio)\n   - When AI is thinking\n   - When AI replies (audio playback)\n   - Different formations for each state\n\n2. **Backend** — A small web server that:\n   - Receives transcribed text from the browser\n   - Sends it to me (Dean/the main agent)\n   - Gets my response\n   - Converts to system voice audio\n   - Streams back to the browser\n\n3. **Real-time voice** — For Safari, I'll need to use the Speech Recognition API. For audio playback, I can use the Audio element.\n\nFor the fairy lights:\n- Canvas-based particle system\n- Particles float around with gentle physics\n- Audio reactive — when sound is detected, particles spread/ripple\n- Different formation for thinking vs speaking vs reply\n\nFor the server:\n- Python Flask or Node.js - Node.js since it's already running things\n- Or... I can integrate this into the Mission Control server or create a new small Express server\n\nActually for Safari, I need to check if Speech Recognition API is available. Let me think...\n\nSafari supports Web Speech API (SpeechRecognition) but it requires a server-side component for some features. For the transcription, I could use:\n- Native browser Web Speech API (SpeechRecognition) - this works in Safari but requires user permission each time\n- Actually on macOS Safari, the SpeechRecognition API should work with the system voice\n\nLet me plan the architecture:\n1. `telephone.html` - The frontend with fairy lights, mic toggle, audio playback\n2. `telephone-server.js` - Node.js server that handles the conversation\n\nFor the backend, I need to think about how to integrate with the main agent. Bobby wants this to work with me (Dean). \n\nI'll need a small API server that sits between the frontend and my agent interface. Since I can leverage the existing Gateway at port 8787, I could either extend that directly or spin up a separate Node.js service that routes messages through Telegram. Given the complexity of coordinating these pieces, using the Gateway API might be simpler than building a standalone service, but I need to figure out what endpoints are actually available to me.\n\nFor now, I'll keep it straightforward: a Node.js server that receives transcribed audio, routes it to me through an OpenClaw session, then converts my text response to speech using the `say` command and streams it back. Let me start building the frontend and server components.","thinkingSignature":"f63a7790cc9df5fcde1529efd6d9001b0dc676fb61e925b8329a101318a118d1"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGot it. Building Telephone now — a standalone voice chat app with fairy lights that react to you, thinking, and my replies.\n\n**What I'm building:**\n\n- `~/Desktop/Telephone/telephone.html` — Dark page, fairy lights everywhere, mic toggle button\n- `~/Desktop/Telephone/telephone-server.js` — Small Node.js server to route your text to me and stream audio back\n- Fairy lights react differently to: you speaking → AI thinking → my audio reply\n- Tap mic → talk → I respond via system voice → tap again\n\n**Architecture:**\n- Your mic → real-time transcription (Safari Web Speech API)\n- Transcribed text → Node.js server → me → response → system voice audio → plays back\n- All local, completely separate from the guide project\n\nStarting the build now. This is a bigger one — I'll have it ready and message you when it's up. Give me about 30 minutes.\n\nWhile I build — what's the one-sentence pitch for Telephone? Just so I know what it should feel like when it's done. e.g. *\"A voice-first chat with Dean that feels like talking to a friend, not typing to a chatbot.\"*"}],"api":"anthropic-messa