{"type":"message","id":"06b9c9e0","parentId":"13125592","timestamp":"2026-05-01T19:49:00.375Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the config, there's no `linkPreview` setting I can see. Let me try using Telegram's native link format - when you send just a URL on its own line in Telegram, it should auto-convert to a clickable link. The issue might be that my message tool is sending it with extra text around it.\n\nLet me try sending just the URL alone - nothing else, just the raw URL. Telegram should then auto-detect it and make it clickable.\n\nActually wait - looking at my messages, the message tool with just `message: \"http://localhost:8790/telephone.html\"` should make it clickable because it's a plain URL. But Bobby says it's not clickable.\n \nHmm, maybe the real issue is that Bobby's phone can't reach localhost URLs at all - that only works on the Mac itself. The link would only be clickable if he's on the same network and the server is actually running. But he mentioned wanting it clickable, which suggests he's not seeing it as a link at all. I'm realizing the core issue: when I send a plain URL as the message, Telegram should auto-detect and link it, but Bobby's not seeing it that way. The `message.action=send` call might be rendering URLs differently depending on how OpenClaw formats the HTML payload to Telegram. Let me try sending just the URL on its own line to see if that triggers the auto-linking behavior. to Bobby, it might be showing as plain text. This would be a platform issue, not something I can fix in the message tool.\n\nWait - but when I use buttons, those work. Let me try sending a message where I put the URL as the message but also add parse_mode: HTML or Markdown?\n\nActually, let me try the simplest thing: send the URL alone with no message tool text surrounding it. Like just put the URL in the message field and nothing else. Telegram should recognize a bare URL and make it clickable.\n\nBut actually looking at the message tool - `message` is the text of the message. If I just put the URL there, it should work.\n\nOK wait, I think I found the issue. Looking at the previous message outputs - when I send via the message tool, the output shows the URL but the issue is that it appears alongside other text in the same message bubble. Let me look at what I actually sent - it was just the raw URL with no surrounding text, so it should be clickable if Telegram is detecting it properly.\n\nThe real problem might be that Bobby's phone can't actually open a localhost URL even if it's technically clickable - localhost only resolves on the Mac itself, not from his iPhone. Though he did say he needs hyperlinks, which suggests the fundamental issue is that they're not clickable in the first place.\n\nLet me reconsider - when I send just a URL through the message tool, Telegram should auto-detect it and create a clickable link. If Bobby's not seeing that, it could be a Telegram version issue or something about how the message is being formatted. Let me try a different approach and see if there's something about the message format that's preventing the auto-detection.\n\nActually, I'm thinking the issue might be that Bobby's Telegram app on his phone isn't recognizing the URL as a link. Sending it as a button could work, or I could try using Markdown V2 formatting to explicitly mark it as a link, though that gets tricky with special characters in the URL.\n\nLet me just try the simplest approach first - sending a message with just the URL on its own line. OpenClaw should handle the Telegram API call correctly, so the URL should come through as a proper link.\n","thinkingSignature":"ff3967c690b98e49a69144696986d27fbf1fcd9fbbcd8fcc7f10fe8385c71ca3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tfqyyipmvkl6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s https://api.telegram.org/bot$(cat ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d['