{"type":"message","id":"00d112c2","parentId":"675634a7","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:04:21.790Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"When I use `<a href=\"...\">text</a>` with HTML parse mode, it creates a `text_link` entity - meaning the text \"Open Telephone\" is linked to the URL. This SHOULD show as a clickable link in Telegram.\n\nBut Bobby said the button wasn't showing. Maybe the issue is that the message tool isn't sending with HTML parse mode when I use the presentation parameter.\n\nLet me look at what the message tool actually does with presentation. The docs say:\n- `presentation: {\"blocks\": [{\"type\": \"buttons\", \"buttons\": [{\"label\": \"text\", \"url\": \"https://...\", \"style\": \"primary\"}]}]}`\n\nBut maybe this format isn't actually supported by the Telegram plugin in OpenClaw. \n\nI'm going in circles here - let me just send the link directly through the Telegram API using a curl command and see if that works. If the HTML-formatted link with proper entities shows up as clickable in Telegram, then the message tool just isn't handling the presentation format correctly.","thinkingSignature":"0c17ba4fc0c83d67a12b92d2d6c3c1862ce1ace0d53ed8162bcf3186345c3e91"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dtm5kisvnojk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"TOKEN=$(cat ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d['channels']['telegram']['accounts']['default']['botToken'])\")\n\ncurl -s \"https://api.telegram.org/bot${TOKEN}/sendMessage\" \\\n  -d 'chat_id=8212808444&text=👉 Open Telephone - tap to open the app:\nhttps://bobbys-macbook-air-1.tail358b13.ts.net/telephone.html&parse_mode=HTML&disable_web_page_preview=true' 2>&1 | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print('sent:', d['ok'], 'msg_id:', d.get('result',{}).get('message_id',''))\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":27577,"output":403,"ca