{"type":"message","id":"fc54a09c","parentId":"2ee5989d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:12:47.391Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The buildInlineKeyboard function only maps buttons with `callback_data` — it doesn't support URL buttons! The Telegram inline keyboard only supports `callback_data` for callback buttons or `url` for URL buttons. But the current implementation only looks for `callback_data`, not `url`.\n\nSo the `presentation.blocks[].buttons[]` format uses `callback_data` by design — it was built for interactive buttons that trigger callbacks, not URL buttons.\n\nThe only way to send a URL button is via the `reply_markup` with `url` fields directly. Let me check if the message tool ever passes URL buttons through.\n\nLooking at the build function: `button?.callback_data` — it requires `callback_data`. \n\nBut I'm realizing the presentation blocks format might not be the right approach here. When I sent `reply_markup` with an inline keyboard directly via curl, it worked and showed the button. The message tool must be transforming the presentation format into something else internally — I need to trace through how it actually constructs the Telegram parameters.\n","thinkingSignature":"636b2794cae6d6477383586b407e733bd599b13beece7128ff410d3aba2d37bc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xgwx1lw0fx5g_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"url.*inline\\|inline.*url\\|url.*button\\|button.*url\" /opt/homebrew/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/extensions/telegram/ 2>/dev/null | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":149,"output":278,"cacheRead":64960,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":65387,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777666361324,"responseId":"06443c39ba200f6b38ece5729bdd5ab1"}}
