{"type":"message","id":"de96090c","parentId":"312fa5f5","timestamp":"2026-05-01T20:13:10.839Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The buildInlineKeyboard function only supports `callback_data` buttons, not URL buttons! It filters out any button that doesn't have `callback_data`. This means the current inline keyboard implementation in OpenClaw's Telegram plugin doesn't support URL buttons at all!\n\nThe buttons format I was using with `url` field was being filtered out because the buildInlineKeyboard only looks for `callback_data`. That's why the inline buttons with URLs weren't appearing.\n\nSo the OpenClaw Telegram plugin doesn't actually support inline keyboard buttons with URLs. The `presentation.blocks[].buttons[].url` format I was trying to use isn't implemented.\n\nI need to either:\n1. Find a different way to send a clickable link\n\n\n2. Use the raw Telegram API directly (which I was doing with curl)\n\nThe raw API with `reply_markup` containing URL buttons works fine, but the OpenClaw message tool's `presentation` format doesn't support URL buttons. Since the HTML `<a href>` link IS clickable according to Bobby, maybe I should go back to using the HTML format with `<a href=\"...\">` and `parse_mode=HTML`.\n\nLooking at what Bobby said about the last 4 messages working, the issue is that links sent as plain text URLs in my responses aren't clickable - they're just showing as regular text in the chat. But Bobby can click on links that are formatted with HTML `<a href>` tags. The problem is I'm not consistently using the HTML format when sending links in my text responses. I'm realizing that OpenClaw's `presentation` format only supports `callback_data` buttons for inline keyboards, not URL buttons—the `url` field gets filtered out. Since curl directly calls the Telegram API and works fine with URL buttons, I should check if there's a way to pass `reply_markup` through OpenClaw's message tool instead.\n\nLooking at the HTML formatting approach more closely, it seems the Telegram bot API supports `<a href=\"...\">text</a>` with `parse_mode=HTML` and can recognize links even without explicit `parse_mode`. The fact that some of my recent messages had clickable links suggests they might have been formatted differently—possibly through direct API calls with proper URL handling rather than through OpenClaw's standard message formatting. I need to figure out what's actually working versus what's being filtered out.\n\nThe real issue is that `presentation.blocks[].buttons[].url` doesn't work because OpenClaw's inline keyboard builder only accepts `callback_data`, not URL buttons. My best path forward is either calling the Telegram API directly with curl to bypass OpenClaw's limitations, finding an OpenClaw-native solution, or accepting that Bobby needs to copy-paste links. But since Bobby mentioned the last 4 messages had working links, I should look at what I actually sent in those messages versus the non-working ones to understand the pattern. Looking at the send-bzTgoQhn.js code, the inline keyboard only supports `callback_data` buttons, not URL buttons—so that approach won't work. I'm realizing I need a different strategy entirely.\n\nI could create a proper Telegram bot command or use a URL shortener, but the most straightforward solution is to just send the URL as plain text since Telegram automatically makes any URL starting with http:// or https:// clickable. The issue Bobby was experiencing might have been a false alarm from the screenshot not fully loading, or the links genuinely weren't clickable. Let me send it as a proper HTTPS URL and see if that resolves the problem. I'm realizing the issue might be with how the HTTPS Tailscale link is being sent—it should render as clickable in Telegram since it's a proper URL, so either something was wrong with the link itself or there's a Telegram caching delay on Bobby's end. Let me try sending a fresh direct HTTPS link to see if that works. I need to find a way to make this consistently clickable for Bobby. Let me set up a proper link shortener using Cloudflare Workers or a similar service, which would give me a reliable, clean URL that Telegram will definitely recognize as a link. Alternatively, I could just send the link as plain text formatted as a proper URL, though that's less guaranteed to be clickable. Let me try the straightforward approach first since it seems to work better than whatever was happening before.\n","thinkingSignature":"5eed50fb0abcf58f9a9ce12d066687636f491ef306f54102560e80db2ab9eb8d"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nI see the issue. OpenClaw's inline button format only supports callback buttons, not URL buttons — the `url` field gets stripped out. That's why the buttons weren't showing up.\n\nThe HTML `<a href>` format DOES work though — Telegram makes those clickable. Let me verify the Tailscale HTTPS link is working:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_k524rgwph1y6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -sI \"https://bobbys-macbook-air-1.tail358b13.ts.net/telephone.html\" 2>&1 | head -3"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":219,"output":999,"cacheRead":65088,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":66306,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777666373539,"responseId":"06443c45fb7334e709674b8c06f20d4a"}}
